Absolutely. In your Jenkins job you can spin up a temporary Docker image just for building. Here’s a snippet of a Jenkinsfile that does that:

```groovy
pipeline { agents { label 'docker' } stages {
    stage('Build') {
        agent { label 'docker' }
        steps {
            // Build the container with your Rust code + cgmlut libs
            sh '''\n                docker build -t game-builder:ci .
            '''
            // Push image to a private registry (optional)
            sh 'docker push myrepo.com/game-builder:ci'
        }
    }
} }```
Crucially, the Dockerfile above already installs system libraries that cgmlut depends on, so no extra Cargo steps are needed. Cargo builds its own dependencies, and the image is cached between runs.

